                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-155228 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-chicago-ill tag-families-and-family-life des-families-and-family-life geo-chicago-ill news_keywords-chicago-2 news_keywords-family-2" id="post-155228">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A Relative Loss</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Peter Orner			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-12-10T23:27:33+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">December 10, 2014 6:27 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 10, 2014 6:27 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Call this a Chicago story. It&#x2019;s true, though I&#x2019;ve never understood why that matters. It seems a cheap way of looking at a story, to judge it by whether or not it actually occurred. The only question is:
                                        Does it rattle the soul or doesn&#x2019;t it?</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We had a bachelor uncle, Uncle Harry, and my brother and I loved him. He wasn&#x2019;t really our uncle. He was my grandmother&#x2019;s first cousin. But we were, my grandmother said, the only family he had left. My
                                        grandmother never had much use for the man herself. <span id="more-155228"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/11/opinion/11PRIVATE/11PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/11/opinion/11PRIVATE/11PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/11/opinion/11PRIVATE/11PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" id="100000003297486"
                                                    width="480" height="476" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="476">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> William Exley</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I think of him bursting in the back door of my grandparents&#x2019; house on Pine Point Drive in a wet trench coat, rain pouring down from the brim of his hat to the kitchen floor, shouting, &#x201C;Hallo! Hallo! Anybody
                                        ashore?&#x201D; My brother and I would sprint to the kitchen and he&#x2019;d kneel down and offer up his nose. &#x201C;Honk the schnozz, go ahead and honk it!&#x201D; A monster of a nose, flabby, pockmarked, and
                                        when we squeezed his nostrils together he&#x2019;d honk like a frantic goose. Since then I&#x2019;ve heard honking geese who had nothing on Harry. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So we loved him, though we got the gist from the rest of the family that he was a half-drunk loser who worked in the post office above Congress Parkway. Can you imagine? A member of our family, a postal clerk? A nearly
                                        70-year-old man lifting boxes all day for a living? According to my grandfather, a banker, Uncle Harry was also a card carrying Socialist of the &#x201C;Emma Goldman type,&#x201D; by which he meant that Harry not
                                        only had rabble-rouser tendencies, he was a Jew with rabble-rouser tendencies, which was a different kettle of fish altogether and especially outrageous given all the bounty this country had shared with Jews. And
                                        it is true that when Uncle Harry did come to us out of the night he would often deliver a short diatribe on the day&#x2019;s news from what my grandfather called an anticapitalist perspective. Unelected Jerry Ford
                                        pardons Tricky Dick for the health of our democracy? Holy moly, if we&#x2019;re that sick we&#x2019;re already dead&#x2026;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Harry,&#x201D; my grandmother would say, &#x201C;Why don&#x2019;t you take off your coat and stay awhile?&#x201D; which was her way of saying exactly the opposite. He never did stay awhile. He never did take
                                        off his coat. As far as I can remember, Uncle Harry never stepped past the kitchen of the old house on Pine Point. Encouraging Harry to stay was the best way to get rid of him. That and my grandfather&#x2019;s not
                                        so discreetly slipping him a check. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We were the only family he had. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Every time I drive under the old post office on Congress, I think of him, of Harry, long dead; he&#x2019;d have to be long, long dead by now. Harry exploding through the back door bearing rain in his hat, throwing me
                                        up in the air so my head clonked the kitchen ceiling. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Things happened. Our parents split up. There was near bankruptcy. There was serious illness. What was left of my family was pulled in different directions and there were fewer and fewer occasions for all of us to get
                                        together at my grandparents&#x2019; house on Pine Point Drive. Years piled up, a decade. In 1986, when I was a senior in high school, my brother called me from college. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Hey, whatever happened to Harry?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Uncle Harry?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;You know any other Harrys?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;He&#x2019;s at the post office,&#x201D; I said. &#x201C;Where else would he be?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;He&#x2019;d be in his mid-80s by now, at least.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Maybe he&#x2019;s dead.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Wouldn&#x2019;t we have heard? Wouldn&#x2019;t there have been a funeral?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I rode my bike over to my father&#x2019;s house, the house I grew up in, the house we&#x2019;d decamped from when my mother decided she couldn&#x2019;t live with my father a minute longer. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Harry?&#x201D; my father said. &#x201C;He&#x2019;s dead.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;How do you know?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My father went silent, a rare thing. We were in the kitchen at the round kitchen table that was always too small for the four of us. When we ate our knees used to touch. Now my father and I sat at this same table and
                                        tried to pretend nobody was missing.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I have no idea,&#x201D; my father said. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My grandparents didn&#x2019;t know, either. They couldn&#x2019;t remember the last time they&#x2019;d heard from him. By then my aunt, their daughter, was so ill they had no grief left to spare.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nobody even had a phone number for the man. Harry would either show up at family gatherings or he wouldn&#x2019;t, and when he did, like I said, he never stayed long. And yet that year I was an intrepid high school
                                        reporter. It was I, Peter Orner, who broke the story that our local hot dog place, Nathan&#x2019;s, was being forced (under threat!) to change its name by an evil empire of a hot dog corporation from New York City.
                                        And so I became obsessed, for a while anyway, with finding Uncle Harry. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I checked with the post office. He&#x2019;d retired in 1979. I checked his last known address, a small apartment on Irving Park Road. He&#x2019;d moved out that same year and hadn&#x2019;t left any forwarding address.
                                        For years his mail had been returned to sender. A neighbor did tell me that she remembered Harry but that it was rare that you were in the hall with him at the same time. &#x201C;You know how it is,&#x201D; she
                                        said. &#x201C;Maybe he&#x2019;d wait to come out until there were no more footsteps. Some are like that.&#x201D; I remember how much this surprised me at the time. He&#x2019;d always been so garrulous with us. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I checked hospitals, nursing homes, cemeteries. I learned that the Cook County Morgue stores hundreds of unclaimed bodies, and that pauper burials happen across the city every day. Chicago is, of course, vast beyond
                                        any imagination, and I&#x2019;ve never been a very good reporter. And so I mostly just drove around smoking joints with my friend Marcus in my mother&#x2019;s Corolla, while Marcus yelled out the window at old men
                                        standing on corners, &#x201C;Hey you, you &#x2014; aren&#x2019;t you Uncle Harry?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What&#x2019;s true about this story is not just that it happened &#x2014; which it did; somewhere along the line my family lost track of Harry &#x2014; but that even after we discovered he&#x2019;d vanished, it didn&#x2019;t
                                        really shake us up. It became, after a while, almost normal, run-of-the-mill, to lose someone in this way, even one of our own. A family joke: Call me, don&#x2019;t pull a Harry. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Here&#x2019;s what I think about now. He was a man who, according to my grandfather, never left the city of Chicago. He&#x2019;d been too old for World War II and besides, even if he had been called up, he would have
                                        found a way out of it, Harry being a pacifist (which went hand in hand, my grandfather said, with his otherwise pinko nature). But I wonder if he didn&#x2019;t, in the end, wander away to die in some new place.
                                        Somewhere he might have been even more anonymous than he already was. You could still in the &#x2019;80s drop off the face of the earth. It&#x2019;s almost comforting to think about today. To be so out of reach
                                        even the debt collectors with their databases can&#x2019;t find you. If Harry owes somebody money, which I&#x2019;m sure he does, then they&#x2019;ll probably find his bones somewhere, someday. This might have made
                                        the man in the wet trench coat laugh. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There is something graceful about the idea of simply walking away, and I like to think of Harry in some smaller Midwestern city, just big enough to get lost in but not so small he&#x2019;d be noticed. Rockford or Peoria,
                                        Ill., or Muscatine, Iowa, just across the Mississippi River. After wandering the city for a few days, he spends the last of his money on a couple of drinks before going back to his semi-furnished room. In my memory
                                        of him he was a jolly fat man but then again he never took that coat off so maybe he was thinner underneath than he always seemed. He lies, in Muscatine, on the bed with his shoes on and waits.</p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//peterorner.net/ ">Peter Orner</a> is the author, most recently, of the collection of short stories &#x201C;Last Car Over the Sagamore Bridge.&#x201D;</em></p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
